Social Media Analytics End Term Project¶

Topic:- Whistlepodu Twitter Analysis¶

Introduction:-¶

Indian Premier League is one of the popular cricket event in the world. Many Star Players, Retired Players, Youngsters play this event to showcase their talent. The Dataset which i am working is about the Tweets of Chennai Super Kings . "#Whistlepodu" . It consists of tweets right from the beginning of the IPL Season this year 2019. Timeline Includes March 20 th 2019 to May 14 th 2019. It consists of all the information like datetime,Username,ID,tweet/text etc.Around 38568 tweets are present in between the above mentioned timeline. So, lets get deeper into the Analysis..¶

1) TimeLine of DataSet¶

As the first match was held on 23-Mar-2019, the Tweets started prior to three days before the first match of the Season. This shows the fan base of CSK and one and only MSDhoni. Coming to the end of the Tweets, after the Finale between Mumbai and Chennai on May 12 2019. The fans continued to tweet to show their love and support.¶

Code used to Scrape the Twitter Data¶

In [ ]:
#####  
import json
import glob
import os

SAVE_TWEET_PATH = 'C:/Users/nsidd/Downloads/TweetScraper-master/Data/tweet/'
SAVE_USER_PATH = './Data/user/'
SAVE_TWEET_DB='C:/Users/nsidd/Downloads/TweetScraper-master/'
SAVE_USER_DB='./Data/'
def readTweets():
	files=glob.iglob(SAVE_TWEET_PATH+'**/*',recursive=True)
	tweets_list=[]
	
	for __file__ in files:

		with open(__file__,"r",encoding="utf-8") as f:
			d = json.load(f)
			tweets_list.append(d)
	return pd.DataFrame(tweets_list)
def readUsers():
	files=glob.iglob(SAVE_USER_PATH+'**/*',recursive=True)
	users_list=[]
	
	for __file__ in files:
		
		with open(__file__) as f:
			d = json.load(f)
			users_list.append(d)
	return pd.DataFrame(users_list)

def saveUsers(data):
	if not os.path.exists(SAVE_USER_DB):
		os.mkdir(SAVE_USER_DB)
	data.to_csv(SAVE_USER_DB+"Users.csv",encoding='utf-8',index=False)

def saveTweets(data):
	if not os.path.exists(SAVE_TWEET_DB):
		os.makedirs(SAVE_TWEET_DB)
	data.to_csv(SAVE_TWEET_DB+'Tweets.csv',encoding='utf-8',index=False)

if __name__ == '__main__':
	data=readTweets()
	saveTweets(data)

Hashtags¶

By using regular expressions, we can extract the hashtags and saving in a separate column¶

In [29]:
import re #regular Expressions
In [30]:
def find_hashtags(text):                                 
    '''This function will extract hashtags'''
    return re.findall('(#[A-Za-z]+[A-Za-z0-9-_]+)', text)
In [31]:
tweets['hashtags']=tweets.text.apply(find_hashtags)

In [37]:
# take the rows from the hashtag columns where there are actually hashtags
hashtags_list_df = tweets.loc[
                       tweets.hashtags.apply(
                           lambda hashtags_list: hashtags_list !=[]
                       ),['hashtags']]
In [38]:
# create dataframe where each use of hashtag gets its own row
flattened_hashtags_df = pd.DataFrame(
    [hashtag for hashtags_list in hashtags_list_df.hashtags
    for hashtag in hashtags_list],
    columns=['hashtags'])

In [40]:
# count of appearances of each hashtag
popular_hashtags = flattened_hashtags_df.groupby('hashtags').size()\
                                        .reset_index(name='counts')\
                                        .sort_values('counts', ascending=False)\
                                        .reset_index(drop=True)

Visual Representation of Tweets¶

In [42]:
# number of times each hashtag appears
counts = flattened_hashtags_df.groupby(['hashtags']).size()\
                              .reset_index(name='counts')\
                              .counts

# define bins for histogram                              
my_bins = np.arange(0,counts.max()+400, 400)-0.5

# plot histogram of tweet counts
plt.figure()
plt.hist(counts, bins = my_bins)
plt.xlabels = np.arange(1,counts.max()+400, 400)
plt.xlabel('hashtag number of appearances')
plt.ylabel('frequency')
plt.yscale('log', nonposy='clip')
plt.show()

From the above figure, we can say that many number of hashtags were occured at the start of the season and gradually decreases¶

Cleaning the Tweets¶

The Below function removes the stemmer , emojis, space,hashtags,punctuations etc¶

In [56]:
# DEFING ALL THE FUNCTIONS NEEDED FOR CLEANING THE TEXT
import re # regular expressions
import string # to accept string 
import nltk # it is a text processing libraries for tokenization, parsing, classification, stemming, tagging and semantic reasoning.
from nltk.corpus import stopwords # particular words which are not neccesary in english
from nltk.stem import PorterStemmer# we use stemmer to remove the "ing" of words
def clean_text(text):
    ps=PorterStemmer()
    text1 = re.sub(r'^https?:\/\/.*[\r\n]*', '', text)#remove url
    print(text1)
    text1=re.sub('[^\w\s#@/:%.,_-]', '', flags=re.UNICODE)#remove emojis
    print(text1)
    text1=re.sub("\s+"," ",x) # removing the space
    print(text1)
    text1=re.sub('#[\w]+', '', x) # removing 'hastags'
    print(text1)
    text_cleaned=" ".join([x for x in text1 if x not in string.punctuation])# remove punctuations
    print(text_cleaned)
    text_cleaned=text_cleaned.lower() #converting all words upper cases into lower case
    print(text_cleaned)
    text_cleaned=text_cleaned.split(" ")# splitting the words with space if neccessary
    print(text_cleaned)
    text_tokens=[token for token in text_cleaned if token not in STOPWORDS] # Prints list of all tokens in the document
    stem_words=[ps.stem(stem) for stem in text_tokens ] # the stem of all tokens in the document
    text=" ".join(stem_words)
    text_cleaned=re.sub(' +',' ',text)# for removing the extra space
    return text_cleaned

To remove the Url we use the below syntax for a clean tweet¶

In [57]:
tweets1['cleaned_text']=tweets1['text'].apply(lambda x:re.sub('http.*','',x)) # removing the URL
tweets1['cleaned_text']=tweets1['cleaned_text'].apply(lambda x:re.sub("\s+"," ",x))# removing the space

from vaderSentiment.vaderSentiment import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer
analyser = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
In [91]:
def sentiment_analyzer_scores(sentence):
    score = analyser.polarity_scores(sentence)
    #print(score)
    return score
In [92]:
def compound_score(text):
    sc=sentiment_analyzer_scores(text)
    return sc['compound']

In [98]:
def emotion(score):
    if score>0.5:
        return "positive"
    if score<0.5:
        return "negative"
    if score==0.5:
        return "neutral"

Based on the Score the emotions are seggregated like Positive,negative,neutral¶

#### Below Function splits positive and negative tweets
In [106]:
def getMostCommon(cleaned_text,topn=20):
    text_cleaned=" ".join(cleaned_text)
    tokenised_tweets=text_cleaned.split(" ")
    freq_counter=Counter(tokenised_tweets)
    return freq_counter.most_common(topn)

Plotting most 50 words in positive words & negative words¶

In [114]:
def plotMostCommonWords(cleaned_text,topn=50,title="Positive Tweets",color="blue",axis=None):
    top_words=getMostCommon(cleaned_text,topn=topn)
    data=pd.DataFrame()
    data['words']=[val[0] for val in top_words]
    data['freq']=[val[1] for val in top_words]
    if axis!=None:
        sns.barplot(y='words',x='freq',data=data,color=color,ax=axis).set_title(title+" top "+str(topn))
    else:
        sns.barplot(y='words',x='freq',data=data,color=color).set_title(title+" top "+str(topn))
In [115]:
from matplotlib import rcParams

"Chennai ipl","Msdhoni","csk","thala" and someother impacts the reviews-which are present in both negative and positive reviews¶

"Love","best" are present in positive tweets and not there in negative ones¶

"out","live" are present in negative tweets and not there in positive tweets¶

So, these Unigrams could't give much information and also could'nt figure out positive tweets and negative tweets because Unigrams takes only one token.¶

Bigrams:-¶

From the above Unigrams as we could'nt figure out the positive and negative tweets we can go much deeper and use two tokens to get more information.
In [116]:
def generateNGram(cleaned_text,n=2):# bigram          #Writing a function for Ngram where n=2(bigram)
    tokens=cleaned_text.split(" ")
    ngrams = zip(*[tokens[i:] for i in range(n)])         
    return ["_".join(ngram) for ngram in ngrams]
In [117]:
positive_tweets_bigrams=[" ".join(generateNGram(cleaned_text)) for cleaned_text in positive_tweets]
negative_tweets_bigrams=[" ".join(generateNGram(cleaned_text)) for cleaned_text in negative_tweets]

Trigrams:-¶

       Lets see trigrams using three tokens for a better outcome
In [122]:
def generateNGram(cleaned_text,n=3):# trigram
    tokens=cleaned_text.split(" ")
    ngrams = zip(*[tokens[i:] for i in range(n)])
    return ["_".join(ngram) for ngram in ngrams]
In [123]:
positive_tweets_trigrams=[" ".join(generateNGram(cleaned_text)) for cleaned_text in positive_tweets]
negative_tweets_trigrams=[" ".join(generateNGram(cleaned_text)) for cleaned_text in negative_tweets]

K-Means Clustering¶

In [142]:
from sklearn.cluster import MiniBatchKMeans
def find_optimal_clusters(tweets1, max_k):
    iters = range(2, max_k+4,5)  # Iteration starting at 2 and ending at 5 clusters with step of 4
    
    sse = []
    for k in iters:
        sse.append(MiniBatchKMeans(n_clusters=k, init_size=1024, batch_size=2048, random_state=20).fit(tweets1).inertia_)
        print('Fit {} clusters'.format(k))
        
    f, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1)
    ax.plot(iters, sse, marker='o')
    ax.set_xlabel('Cluster Centers')
    ax.set_xticks(iters)
    ax.set_xticklabels(iters)
    ax.set_ylabel('SSE')
    ax.set_title('SSE by Cluster Center Plot')
    
find_optimal_clusters(text,22)

Fit 2 clusters
Fit 7 clusters
Fit 12 clusters
Fit 17 clusters
Fit 22 clusters

In [144]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE
from matplotlib import cm
def plot_tsne_pca(data, labels):
    max_label = max(labels)
    max_items = np.random.choice(range(tweets1.shape[0]), size=3000, replace=False)
    
    pca = PCA(n_components=2).fit_transform(data[max_items,:].todense())
    tsne = TSNE().fit_transform(PCA(n_components=50).fit_transform(data[max_items,:].todense()))
    
    
    idx = np.random.choice(range(pca.shape[0]), size=300, replace=False)
    label_subset = labels[max_items]
    label_subset = [cm.hsv(i/max_label) for i in label_subset[idx]]
    
    f, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 6))
    
    ax[0].scatter(pca[idx, 0], pca[idx, 1], c=label_subset)
    ax[0].set_title('PCA Cluster Plot')
    
    ax[1].scatter(tsne[idx, 0], tsne[idx, 1], c=label_subset)
    ax[1].set_title('TSNE Cluster Plot')
    
plot_tsne_pca(text, clusters)

These are the Clusters¶

PCA Cluster Plot is not better plot for analysis but TSNE Cluster Plot gives a better visuals.¶

In [145]:
def get_top_keywords(tweets1, clusters, labels, n_terms):
    df = pd.DataFrame(tweets1.todense()).groupby(clusters).mean()
    
    for i,r in df.iterrows():
        print('\nCluster {}'.format(i))
        print(','.join([labels[t] for t in np.argsort(r)[-n_terms:]]))
            
get_top_keywords(text, clusters, tfidf.get_feature_names(), 12)

def format_topics_sentences(ldamodel, corpus, texts):
    # Init output
    sent_topics_tweets1 = pd.DataFrame()

    # Get main topic in each document
    for i, row in enumerate(ldamodel[corpus]):
        
        row = sorted(row, key=lambda x: (x[1]), reverse=True)
        # Get the Dominant topic, Perc Contribution and Keywords for each document
        for j, (topic_num, prop_topic) in enumerate(row):
            if j == 0:  # => dominant topic
                wp = ldamodel.show_topic(topic_num)
                topic_keywords = ", ".join([word for word, prop in wp])
                sent_topics_tweets1 = sent_topics_tweets1.append(pd.Series([int(topic_num), round(prop_topic,4), topic_keywords]), ignore_index=True)
            else:
                break
    sent_topics_tweets1.columns = ['Dominant_Topic', 'Perc_Contribution', 'Topic_Keywords']

    # Add original text to the end of the output
    contents = pd.Series(texts)
    sent_topics_tweets1 = pd.concat([sent_topics_tweets1, contents], axis=1)
    return(sent_topics_tweets1)


tweets1_topic_sents_keywords = format_topics_sentences(ldamodel=lda_model, corpus=doc_term_matrix, texts=corpus)

# Format
tweets1_dominant_topic = tweets1_topic_sents_keywords.reset_index()
tweets1_dominant_topic.columns = ['Document_No', 'Dominant_Topic', 'Topic_Perc_Contrib', 'Keywords', 'Text']

In [175]:
def compute_coherence_values(dictionary, corpus, texts, limit, start=2, step=3):
    """
    Compute c_v coherence for various number of topics

    Parameters:
    ----------
    dictionary : Gensim dictionary
    corpus : Gensim corpus
    texts : List of input texts
    limit : Max num of topics

    Returns:
    -------
    model_list : List of LDA topic models
    coherence_values : Coherence values corresponding to the LDA model with respective number of topics
    """
    coherence_values = []
    model_list = []
    for num_topics in range(start, limit, step):
        model = LDA(corpus=doc_term_matrix, id2word=dictionary, num_topics=num_topics, random_state=100,chunksize=1000, passes=50)
        model_list.append(model)
        coherencemodel = CoherenceModel(model=model, texts=tokenised_corpus, dictionary=dictionary, coherence='c_v')
        coherence_values.append(coherencemodel.get_coherence())
        print(coherencemodel.get_coherence())

    return model_list, coherence_values
